President Obama announced his intent to nominate three individuals to key administration posts. The first nominee is Paul Martin, who has been the Deputy Inspector General at the Department of Justice since 2003. Martin has extensive experience in the field, having served as Counselor to the Inspector General and Special Counsel to the Inspector General prior to his current role. He also has a background in journalism and holds a B.A. in Journalism from Pennsylvania State University and a J.D. from Georgetown University School of Law.

The second nominee is Mark R. Rosekind, who is currently the President and Chief Scientist of Alertness Solutions, a scientific consulting firm. Rosekind has a background in sleep and fatigue research and has worked at NASA, where he directed the NASA Fatigue Countermeasures Program and served as Chief of the Aviation Operations Branch. He has also conducted research in various work settings, including transportation, healthcare, public safety, and the military. Rosekind graduated from Stanford University with Honors, obtained his Ph.D. at Yale University, and completed a postdoctoral fellowship at the Brown University Medical School.

The third nominee is Christine H. Fox, who is currently the president of the Center for Naval Analyses. Fox has extensive experience as an analyst and research manager focusing on defense issues, particularly operations. She has been responsible for overseeing CNA's work on operations, cost and acquisition, manpower, readiness, and technology issues. Fox has also served on various task groups and advisory boards, including NASA's Stafford-Covey Return to Flight Task Group. She holds an M.S. in Applied Mathematics from George Mason University and a B.S. in Mathematics from the same institution.